  "summary": {
    "as": "Introduced", 
    "date": "1987-01-08", 
    "text": "Intellectual Property Antitrust Protection Act of 1987 - Provides that agreements to convey rights to use, practice, or sublicense a patented invention, rights to use or sublicense a trade secret including related know how, or rights in a copyrighted work or mask work shall not be deemed to be illegal per se under the Federal antitrust laws or similar State laws. Limits the amount a person may recover in an antitrust claim based on such an agreement to the actual damages sustained, specified interest, and the cost of suit, including a reasonable attorney's fee."
  }, 
